  "prompt": "Do human beings have free will, if so, how can we prove it?",
  "response": "This is a profound philosophical question that has been debated for centuries. There are several perspectives:\n\nArguments for Free Will:\n1. Subjective experience - We feel like we make choices\n2. Moral responsibility requires free will\n3. Quantum mechanics suggests indeterminism\n4. Consciousness appears to allow deliberate decision-making\n\nArguments Against Free Will:\n1. Deterministic physics suggests all actions are predetermined\n2. Neuroscience shows brain activity precedes conscious decisions\n3. Our choices seem influenced by genetics, environment, and prior experiences\n4. Philosophical arguments about causal chains\n\nPotential Proof Approaches:\n1. Philosophical reasoning\n2. Neuroscientific experiments\n3. Quantum indeterminacy research\n4. Subjective phenomenological investigation\n\nCurrent scientific consensus is inconclusive. Most philosophers and scientists recognize complexity in the free will debate, with perspectives ranging from:\n- Hard determinism (no free will)\n- Compatibilism (free will compatible with determinism)\n- Libertarian free will (genuine choice exists)\n\nNo definitive proof exists yet. The question remains an open philosophical and scientific problem requiring continued interdisciplinary research across neuroscience, physics, philosophy, and psychology.\n\nWould you be interested in exploring any of these perspectives in more depth?",
